reviewText: I'm so looking forward to getting this movie.  I remember watching it on TV several years ago and loved it. I recorded it from the TV and have watched several times.  The quality of my VHS tape isn't very good anymore, so it will be wonderful to watch it like it should be.Betty White & Richard Thomas are both great actors and are wonderful in this movie about a woman (White) who wants to take her husband's ashes to a place that was very special to both of them and where he has requested his ashes be spread.  The only problem, it is across the country and her son (Thomas)feels he is too busy to take the time to take her there and that she shouldn't go alone.  So she gets her granddaughter to go with her, without telling her son, and off they go in a funny, sentimental at times, road trip.  And, of course, like she thought he would, her son follows them and the whole family is together when they reach that special place, "Annie's Point".

reviewText: This is a wonderful family movie about a woman who loses her husband and wants to spread his ashes in a place that was very dear to both of them. There is a scene in her son's office with a picture on the wall in the background. It is a picture of Allen Ludden, Betty White's real life husband, who died in 1981 of cancer.

reviewText: Perhaps the only thing more amazing than Betty White's longevity is her talent. She can be comedic and dramatic in the same scene and does it very well. And she makes Annie's Point worth viewing. She portrays a widow who tries to fulfill a promise to her husband to have his ashes scattered over Annie's Point, CA. Her health is precarious and her son is against her driving cross country, but she tricks her granddaughter into going with her without her son's prior knowledge. The trip is as much as a voyage of self discovery for both of them as it is a fulfillment. The script is cliched in places, but Betty White makes it work. Richard Thomas is very good as the son, and Amy Davidson is sweet as the granddaughter. Would recommend it.
